<a id="comment-1184782"></a>


  <article class="single-comment">
    <header>
      <div>
                  <a href="/users/d-sherman/comments" title="View D. Sherman profile.">D. Sherman</a>                          <time>Dec 28th 2011 19:50 GMT</time>
      </div>
    </header>
    <div><p>Obviously, a private investor is welcome to invest in anything he wants. If Mr. Allen has $250 million in venture capital to invest in something risky that might pay off big, good for him. Any new technology developed with his money will at least end up being publicly available, unlike most of the secret military research. Even if the company fails, the knowledge and experience will remain. In this regard it's a bit like all the rich Europeans and East Coast millionaires of the late 19th century who invested heavily in Western mines and railroads. Most of them lost their money, but their money left cities and transportation networks behind that were good for lots of other things.</p>
<p>These gentlemen are probably right that the commercial satellite launch business is where the money will be. A passenger is a one-time expense for an adventurous rich person with money to burn, and there is a rather limited number of such people, but a commercial satellite is a revenue stream that can pencil out very nicely on a balance sheet. What doesn't make sense to me is developing one vehicle to do both. Human-rated spacecraft are inherently much more expensive than those designed to carry only inanimate objects. Why burden the satellite launch vehicle with human-rated systems?</p>
</div>
