<a id="comment-1186882"></a>


  <article class="single-comment">
    <header>
      <div>
                  <a href="/user/2949338/comments" title="View Devils Advocate_1 profile.">Devils Advocate_1</a>                          <time>Dec 30th 2011 8:30 GMT</time>
      </div>
    </header>
    <div><p>[ Fossil American Dec 29th 2011 6:29 GMT<br />
Insanity Triumphs wrote: "...What I would like to see is a nuclear powered rocketship. That obviates the need for the disposable boosters...."<br />
* * *<br />
Trouble is, Newton's Laws of Motion, particularly the second and third law. You need to throw mass at one direction to gain momentum at the other direction. Nuclear power gives you energy. You can use that energy to shoot something out in one direction to gain momentum in the other direction. But what do you shoot out?</p>
<p>There is the ion engine - using nuclear power to shoot charged ion at very high speed. But ions (of anything) are so small thus the momentum you gain is so little. Good for slow acceleration long journeys, but certainly not capable of achieving escape velocity to leave earth. Near term, not much we can do with nuclear power rockets.]</p>
<p>How about a fusion engine- If you could build one? You can throw the fusion product (i.e. He) out of the rear end of the engine-- Like you throw the reaction products out of the rear end of a chemical rocket engine.</p>
<p>[A nearer technology is perhaps “space ladder”. While nearer than escape velocity nuclear rocket, it is still merely a techno-dream at this stage. A super strong long rope of perhaps carbon nanotube for us to climb up and away.]</p>
<p>You can only stay in orbits on the Equatorial plane unless you use a rocket to change your orbit.</p>
<p>[For the long long term, let us not forget, there is no physical law against anti-gravity. The dark energy that is expanding our universe is obviously an anti-gravity force. May be someday we can learn to create and control such force.</p>
<p>Well, folks, get cracking. I sure love to orbit Jupiter and look around Europa... Soon...]</p>
<p>Is anti-gravity still a theoretical construct or a proven phenomenon? </p>
<p>Devil's</p>
</div>
